<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Turkey Preparation</strong> - The cooking method dramatically changes your pairing strategy. A herb-brined turkey with crispy skin calls for medium-bodied wines like Côtes du Rhône or Oregon Pinot Noir that won't be overwhelmed by the savory herbs yet have enough acidity to cut through the fat. Deep-fried turkey demands bigger wines—try a Châteauneuf-du-Pape or Paso Robles Zinfandel to match the intensely rich, caramelized flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Whites at Cellar Temperature for Thanksgiving</strong> - Skip the typical ice-cold service for Thanksgiving whites. Serve Chardonnay and white Rhône blends at 55-58°F instead of the usual 45°F. This slightly warmer temperature allows the wine's texture and oak integration to shine against rich sides like creamy mashed potatoes and green bean casserole, while preventing the wine from being shocked by the warm food temperatures.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Young Reds 2-3 Hours Before Dinner</strong> - Thanksgiving timing is crucial—decant tannic reds like young Cabernet Sauvignon, Barolo, or Northern Rhône Syrah 2-3 hours before your meal starts. This extended aeration softens tannins that would otherwise clash with the meal's sweetness from cranberry sauce and sweet potatoes, while allowing the wine's fruit to emerge and complement the savory elements.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Wines with Natural Acidity for Gravy and Stuffing</strong> - The starch-heavy nature of Thanksgiving sides requires wines with bright acidity to cleanse the palate. Sangiovese-based wines like Chianti Classico or Brunello di Montalcino are perfect—their natural high acidity cuts through sage stuffing and turkey gravy while their earthy undertones complement mushroom and herb flavors without competing.</li>

  <li><strong>Avoid New Oak with Sweet Side Dishes</strong> - Skip heavily oaked wines when serving candied yams, cranberry sauce, or cornbread. The vanilla and spice notes from new oak barrels create flavor confusion with these sweet elements. Instead, choose wines aged in neutral oak or stainless steel, like Cru Beaujolais or unoaked Chardonnay, which provide clean fruit flavors that harmonize rather than compete.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Pinot Noir and Light Reds</strong> - The traditional Thanksgiving table calls for larger wine glasses than usual. Use Burgundy bowls (22-24 oz capacity) for Pinot Noir, Gamay, and lighter reds. The wide bowl concentrates the delicate aromatics that can get lost among competing food aromas, while the thin rim delivers the wine precisely to enhance its silky texture against tender turkey meat.</li>

  <li><strong>Plan Your Wine Timeline Around Multiple Courses</strong> - Start with a crisp Sancerre or Champagne during appetizers, transition to medium-bodied reds like Côtes du Rhône Villages with the main course, and finish with a late-harvest Riesling or vintage Port with pumpkin pie. This progression prevents palate fatigue and ensures each wine enhances its designated course rather than competing with lingering flavors from previous pairings.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose 3-7 Year Old Wines for Optimal Balance</strong> - Thanksgiving's complex flavor profile demands wines with some age that have resolved their tannins and integrated their oak, but haven't lost their fruit vibrancy. A 5-year-old Napa Cabernet Sauvignon or 4-year-old Willamette Valley Pinot Noir provides the perfect balance—mature enough to handle rich gravies and roasted flavors, yet fresh enough to complement the meal's herbaceous and bright elements.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with turkey and all the traditional Thanksgiving sides?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir is the ultimate Thanksgiving wine because its medium body and bright acidity complement turkey's lean meat while its earthy undertones harmonize with stuffing, cranberry sauce, and roasted vegetables. Oregon Pinot Noir or Burgundy work exceptionally well, as their natural acidity cuts through rich gravy and butter-laden sides without overwhelming the delicate turkey flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve white wine or red wine with Thanksgiving dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve both, but prioritize red wine for the main course since turkey's mild flavor and traditional herb seasonings (sage, thyme, rosemary) pair naturally with red wines like Pinot Noir, Côtes du Rhône, or Beaujolais. White wines like Chardonnay or Riesling work beautifully as aperitifs and complement side dishes like sweet potato casserole or green bean almondine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How many bottles of wine do I need for Thanksgiving dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for one bottle per every 2-3 guests, accounting for appetizers, dinner, and dessert wine service over 3-4 hours. For a table of 8, purchase 3-4 bottles: one white for pre-dinner, two reds for the main course, and consider a dessert wine or sparkling for toasts.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget-friendly wine for Thanksgiving that still tastes impressive?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for American Pinot Noir from Oregon's Willamette Valley ($15-25) or French Côtes du Rhône ($12-18), both offering excellent food-pairing versatility without breaking the bank. Alternatively, Spanish Garnacha or Portuguese Douro reds provide rich, crowd-pleasing flavors that complement Thanksgiving's hearty dishes at under $20 per bottle.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing Thanksgiving wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is selecting wines that are too bold or high in alcohol, like Cabernet Sauvignon or Zinfandel, which overpower turkey's delicate flavor and clash with sweet sides like cranberry sauce. These heavy reds also intensify the richness of butter and cream-based sides, creating palate fatigue rather than enhancing the meal's diverse flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair wine with pumpkin pie and other Thanksgiving desserts?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, but choose wines with natural sweetness and complementary spice notes like late-harvest Riesling, Moscato d'Asti, or tawny Port, which echo the cinnamon, nutmeg, and vanilla flavors in traditional pies. For chocolate desserts, consider Ruby Port or Banyuls, while fresh fruit tarts pair beautifully with sparkling wine or light Moscato.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Thanksgiving wine pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—Thanksgiving is perfect for wine beginners because the meal's diverse flavors showcase how wine enhances food, and crowd-pleasing varieties like Pinot Noir and Chardonnay are approachable and widely available. The communal nature of the meal also creates a relaxed environment for tasting and comparing different wines without pressure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What non-alcoholic alternatives pair well with Thanksgiving dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling apple cider offers wine-like complexity with its natural acidity and fruit-forward profile, while pomegranate juice mixed with sparkling water provides tart, cranberry-like flavors that complement turkey beautifully. For more sophistication, try non-alcoholic wines from brands like Ariel or Fre, which maintain the tannin structure and flavor complexity needed for food pairing.</p>
